<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-06T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-06T11:00:00-05:00" n="432" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d432">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">837.01/24: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Panama</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-06T11:00:00-05:00">October 6, 1933—11
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 1:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>137. With reference to press reports Panaman recognition of present
                                government Cuba, acting President Diaz informs me that report is
                                substantially correct and that Panama has chosen to follow the
                                principle of a continuous recognition by instructing its diplomatic
                                representative in Habana to establish conversations with the
                                government there.</p>
                            <p>Acting President thought President Arias might call on Grau San
                                Martín at Habana.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Burdett</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>